Introduction¶

(back to top)

Many times good food is associated with fancy restaurants, where a tasting menu can cost a couple weeks of salary. But there are places where one can satisfy both its palate and wallet. And while most famous rankings focus on fine dining this project aims to highlight those little gems where your meal can be good, pretty and cheap.

We will use data from Tripadvisor to find cheap restaurants and create a map to display them, along with a table with the same information so it can be filtered and manipulated in an easier way.

Web Scraping¶

(back to top)

Tripadvisor doesn't offer any options to download data from their website, so the chosen solution was to do web scraping using selenium web driver.

The scraping posed problems such as restaurants with missing information and different structures depending on wheter there were or not some sections, which were solved by using conditional clauses. It also took a long time to run (around an hour) considering the limited amount of restaurants available (less than 1000), and while this couldn't be completely solved it was dealt by adding tdqm, a smart progress meter to the loop.

The raw data extracted was written to a csv file so it wasn't necessary to run the loop each time the kernel was reseted.

Data Cleansing¶

(back to top)

The data scraped from the website was far from ready to be used for mapping the restaurants. The were characters to be removed, columns to be reformated and rows to be filtered.

Since most of the data is text, we started by setting the whole dataframe as string type.

The restaurants have a global score and some of them also feature sub-scores for items like food, service and value. All af them were casted as numeric, along with the number of reviews they had and their place in the ranking (which includes all the restaurants in Buenos Aires, not only the cheap ones).

Then, the restaurants without any reviews were filtered, because there is no way to know wheter they are good or not without them.

In [5]:
#Scoring columns
temp=['score', 'food', 'service', 'value']

for i in temp:
    restaurants[i] = [j.replace('ui_bubble_rating bubble_','') for j in restaurants[i]]
    restaurants[i] = pd.to_numeric(restaurants[i], errors='coerce')/10

#Rank format
restaurants['rank'] = [i.replace('de 5.004 restaurantes en Buenos Aires','') for i in restaurants['rank']]
restaurants['rank'] = [i.replace('#','') for i in restaurants['rank']]
restaurants['rank'] = pd.to_numeric(restaurants['rank'], errors='coerce')

#Number of reviews
restaurants['nreviews'] = [i.replace(' opiniones','') for i in restaurants['nreviews']]
restaurants['nreviews'] = pd.to_numeric(restaurants['nreviews'], errors='coerce')

restaurants = restaurants[restaurants['nreviews'] > 0]

After the numeric columns, we went trough the address one. The addresses were normalized in order to be ready for the geolocation.

In [6]:
#Addresses format and removing not normalized rows
new_address=[]

for values in restaurants['address']:
    try:
        street=re.search("(.*?)\d+", values).group()+', CABA, Argentina'
    except AttributeError:
        street='Not normalized'
    
    new_address.append(street)

restaurants['new_address']=new_address

restaurants['new_address']=([i
                             .replace('Calle ','')
                             .replace('Avenida ','')
                             .replace('Av. ','')
                             for i in restaurants['new_address']])

restaurants = restaurants[restaurants['new_address'] != 'Not normalized']

Mapping¶

(back to top)

In order to position a point in the map, it is necessary to have its coordinates (longitude and latitude). We only got the address from the website, so we used geopy's nominatim geocoder to complete the task (which is why it was important to normalize the addresses). The limitation that it has is that it alows one request per second, so it takes a while for large amounts of addresses.

In [8]:
#Obtaining coordinates
geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="restaurants_coord")
geocode = RateLimiter(geolocator.geocode, min_delay_seconds=1)

tqdm.pandas()
restaurants['location'] = restaurants['new_address'].progress_apply(geocode)

restaurants['point'] = restaurants['location'].apply(lambda loc: tuple(loc.point) if loc else None)

We filtered the restaurants without coordinates and then we split them in latitude and longitude. With this done, the data was ready to be used for the map.













In [9]:



    


#Keeping only restaurants with coordinates
restaurants = restaurants[restaurants.point.notnull()]

#Formatting coordinates 
restaurants['point']=restaurants['point'].astype(str)
restaurants[['latitude', 'longitude', 'altitude']] = restaurants.point.str.split(",", expand=True)
restaurants['latitude'] = [i.replace('(','') for i in restaurants['latitude']]

restaurants['latitude']=pd.to_numeric(restaurants['latitude'], errors='coerce')
restaurants['longitude']=pd.to_numeric(restaurants['longitude'], errors='coerce')

restaurants.drop(['address','point','altitude'], axis=1, inplace=True)

restaurants.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

To display the restaurants on the map we used folium, a library built over the Leaflet.js Maps.













In [10]:



    


m = folium.Map(location=[-34.6083,-58.4212], tiles='cartodbpositron', zoom_start=12)


marker_cluster = MarkerCluster(name='cheap restaurants', overlay=True, control=False, icon_create_function=None)

for i in range(len(restaurants['latitude'])):
    location = restaurants['latitude'][i], restaurants['longitude'][i]
    marker = folium.Marker(location=location)
    popup = ('<b>Name:</b> {} <br><b>Cuisines:</b> {} <br><b>Rank:</b> {} <br><b>Reviews:</b> {} <br><b>Score:</b> {}  <br><b>Address:</b> {} <br><b>Phone:</b> {} <br><b>Website:</b> <a href={}>abc</a>'
             .format(re.sub(r'[^\w]', ' ', unidecode.unidecode(restaurants['name'][i])), 
                     restaurants['cuisines'][i],
                     restaurants['rank'][i],
                     restaurants['nreviews'][i],
                     restaurants['score'][i], 
                     restaurants['new_address'][i], 
                     restaurants['phone'][i], 
                     restaurants['website'][i]))
    folium.Popup(popup, max_width=500).add_to(marker)
    marker_cluster.add_child(marker)

marker_cluster.add_to(m)

folium.LayerControl().add_to(m)
